Based on your 

.env.development
 file, your project expects Redis to run on localhost port 6379 with no password.

You can start a Redis instance that perfectly matches your configuration by running the following command in your terminal (or command prompt / PowerShell):

powershell
docker run --name zarva-redis -p 6379:6379 -d redis:alpine
What this command does:
docker run: Starts a new container.
--name zarva-redis: Assigns the name "zarva-redis" to your container so you can easily identify it.
-p 6379:6379: Maps port 6379 inside the container to port 6379 on your local machine (which matches your REDIS_PORT=6379 in 

.env.development
).
-d: Runs the container in the background (detached mode) so it doesn't block your terminal.
redis:alpine: Uses the official, lightweight Alpine-based Redis image.
Useful commands to manage it later:

To stop it: docker stop zarva-redis
To start it again: docker start zarva-redis
To view logs: docker logs zarva-redis
Bonus: I also noticed your 

.env.development
 expects a local MySQL database. If you also want to run the MySQL database inside Docker with the same credentials, you can run:

powershell
docker run --name zarva-mysql -p 3306:3306 -e MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD=Vs@123456 -e MYSQL_DATABASE=zarva_dev -d mysql:8.0









firebase
--------
To make the google-services.json config values accessible to Firebase SDKs, you need the Google services Gradle plugin.


Kotlin DSL (build.gradle.kts)

Groovy (build.gradle)
Add the plugin as a dependency to your project-level build.gradle file:

Root-level (project-level) Gradle file (<project>/build.gradle):
plugins {
  // ...

  // Add the dependency for the Google services Gradle plugin
  id 'com.google.gms.google-services' version '4.4.4' apply false

}
Then, in your module (app-level) build.gradle file, add both the google-services plugin and any Firebase SDKs that you want to use in your app:

Module (app-level) Gradle file (<project>/<app-module>/build.gradle):
plugins {
  id 'com.android.application'

  // Add the Google services Gradle plugin
  id 'com.google.gms.google-services'

  ...
}

dependencies {
  // Import the Firebase BoM
  implementation platform('com.google.firebase:firebase-bom:34.9.0')


  // TODO: Add the dependencies for Firebase products you want to use
  // When using the BoM, don't specify versions in Firebase dependencies
  // https://firebase.google.com/docs/android/setup#available-libraries
}
By using the Firebase Android BoM, your app will always use compatible Firebase library versions. Learn more
After adding the plugin and the desired SDKs, sync your Android project with Gradle files.


