### 📝 React Native Firebase & Expo Notifications Manifest Merger Conflict

**The Problem:**
When using both `@react-native-firebase/messaging` and `expo-notifications`, the Android build fails during the `processDebugMainManifest` task (Manifest Merger). Both libraries try to set the default notification color in the Android manifest, causing a conflict because Gradle doesn't know which one to prioritize.

**The Solution:**
You must explicitly tell the Android build system to override the Firebase default with your app's default by adding the `tools:replace` attribute to the `meta-data` tag in `android/app/src/main/AndroidManifest.xml`.

**Steps to Fix:**
1. Open `android/app/src/main/AndroidManifest.xml`
2. Locate the `meta-data` tag for `com.google.firebase.messaging.default_notification_color`
3. Add `tools:replace="android:resource"` to the end of the tag.

**Example Fix:**
```xml
<!-- Before -->
<meta-data android:name="com.google.firebase.messaging.default_notification_color" android:resource="@color/notification_icon_color"/>

<!-- After (Fixed) -->
<meta-data android:name="com.google.firebase.messaging.default_notification_color" android:resource="@color/notification_icon_color" tools:replace="android:resource"/>
```

> **⚠️ Expo Prebuild Warning:** If you ever delete your `/android` folder and run `npx expo prebuild` again, this manual change will be lost and the build will fail again. To make this permanent, you would need to write a custom Expo Config Plugin to inject `tools:replace` automatically during the prebuild phase.
***

### 📝 TODO: Firebase Phone Auth Play Integrity Setup

**The Problem (`[auth/missing-client-identifier]`):**
Firebase Phone Auth fails on local emulators/devices because Google Play Integrity (SafetyNet) blocks the SMS request, thinking it's a bot. It requires the app's cryptographic SHA keys to be registered in the Firebase Console to allow the request through.

**Status:** 🔴 NOT DONE

**Steps to Fix:**
1. Open terminal and run: `cd zarva-mobile/android && ./gradlew signingReport`
2. Scroll up to the **`Variant: debug`** output.  
3. Copy the **SHA1** and **SHA-256** keys.
4. Go to [Firebase Console](https://console.firebase.google.com/) -> Project Settings -> General.
5. Under your Android app (`com.zarva.app`), click **Add fingerprint**.
6. Paste both the SHA1 and SHA-256 keys.
7. Wait 3-5 minutes, hit `R` in Metro, and test SMS again..




